== Abstract

*Introduction:* Pediatric sepsis is one of the leading causes of morbidity and mortality in pediatric intensive care units (PICU) worldwide. In 2024, new international consensus criteria for pediatric sepsis were published, introducing the Phoenix Sepsis Score as a validated diagnostic tool. Its predictive capacity for 30-day mortality in Latin American populations requires local evaluation.

*Objective:* To evaluate the predictive value of the Phoenix Sepsis Score for 30-day mortality in pediatric patients with sepsis admitted to the pediatric intensive care unit.

*Methods:* Observational, analytical, prospective cohort study. Patients aged 1 month to 17 years with a diagnosis of sepsis admitted to the PICU will be included. The Phoenix score will be calculated at admission, and patients will be followed for 30 days. Prognostic performance will be determined through ROC curve analysis, sensitivity, specificity, positive and negative predictive values, and likelihood ratios.

*Expected results:* The Phoenix scale is expected to demonstrate an area under the ROC curve ≥ 0.75 for predicting 30-day mortality, with comparable or superior performance to previously used pediatric organ dysfunction scores.

*Keywords:* pediatric sepsis, Phoenix Sepsis Score, mortality, predictive value, organ dysfunction, pediatric intensive care.
